    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-09-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-09-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="261"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d261">
                <head>261. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d261fn1"
                        >Source: Department of State, Office of the Secretariat Staff, <persName
                            corresp="#p_VCR_1">Cyrus R. Vance</persName>, Secretary of
                        State—1977–1980, Lot 84D241, Box 10, [untitled folder]. Secret; <gloss
                            target="#t_Nodis_1">Nodis</gloss>. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJF_1">Dobbins</persName>; cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_VGS_1">Vest</persName>; approved in <gloss target="#t_SS_1"
                            >S/S</gloss>. The meeting took place in <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                            >Vance</persName>’s office.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-09-16">September 16, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <list>
                            <head>US</head>
                            <item>The Secretary</item>
                            <item>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HPC_1">Philip
                                    Habib</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_HAA_1">Arthur A.
                                    Hartman</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Assistant Secretary <persName corresp="#p_VGS_1">George S.
                                    Vest</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_DJF_1">James F. Dobbins</persName>, <gloss
                                    target="#t_EURWE_1">EUR/WE</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>(Notetaker)</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <list>
                            <head>FRANCE</head>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">Louis de Guiringaud</persName>,
                                Foreign</item>
                            <item>Minister</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_LFd_1">Francois de Laboulaye</persName>,
                                Political</item>
                            <item>Director</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Pakistan and Non-Proliferation</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">De Guiringaud</persName> related that, in a meeting
                    on September 8 with Pakistani Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_SA_3">Aga
                        Shahi</persName>,<note n="2" xml:id="d261fn2">According to telegram 26348
                        from Paris, September 10, <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">de
                            Guiringaud</persName>’s meeting with <persName corresp="#p_SA_3"
                            >Shahi</persName> took place on September 7. See <ref target="#d260fn2"
                            >footnote 2, Document 260</ref>.</note> he had told <persName
                        corresp="#p_SA_3">Aga Shahi</persName> that <pb facs="0677" n="632"
                        xml:id="pg_632"/> France had a contract to furnish Pakistan with a plant
                    which was capable of reprocessing used nuclear fuel in a manner that would
                    enable it to be used again to fuel reactors. He had then proposed to have plans
                    for this plant restructured, along the lines <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">de
                        Guiringaud</persName> had earlier discussed with Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="#p_HAA_1">Hartman</persName>.<note n="3" xml:id="d261fn3">See <ref
                            target="#d260fn3">footnote 3, Document 260</ref>.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">De Guiringaud</persName> told <persName
                        corresp="#p_SA_3">Aga Shahi</persName> that the French government would, in
                    due course, open conversations with Pakistan to rewrite certain parts of the
                    agreement.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SA_3">Aga Shahi</persName> had been very surprised,
                        <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">de Guiringaud</persName> said. <persName
                        corresp="#p_GLd_1">De Guiringaud</persName> had been forced to endure an
                    hour-long series of complaints about discrimination against Pakistan, vis-a-vis
                    India, in the nuclear field. <persName corresp="#p_SA_3">Aga Shahi</persName>
                    had talked about the Canadian and US assistance to India in the nuclear field,
                    including assistance on breeder technology. He claimed that India had been able
                    to become a nuclear power as a result of such assistance. He had insisted that
                    Pakistan must receive treatment comparable to that given India. Something must
                    be done for Pakistan or assistance to India must be cut back.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">De Guiringaud</persName> said that he had, as a
                    result of this conversation, initiated a study of France’s nuclear relationship
                    with India. The Secretary said that he would have a paper prepared for <persName
                        corresp="#p_GLd_1">de Guiringaud</persName> outlining the current state of
                    the US nuclear relationship with India. He said that the United States had
                    agreed to provide a certain amount of fuel for the Tarapur reactor. The United
                    States had also talked to India about the need to accept full-scope safeguards.
                    The Indians had agreed to consider this seriously. <persName corresp="#p_HPC_1"
                        >Habib</persName> added that there had been some general discussion on this
                    issue with <persName corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName> who had indicated that
                    the Indians would not conduct further nuclear tests. The Secretary said that
                        <persName corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName> personally had been clear on
                    this, and that he rejected testing. <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">De
                        Guiringaud</persName> noted, however, that not all of <persName
                        corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName>’s subordinates were in agreement with his
                    position, nor was <persName corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName> necessarily
                    capable of controlling these people.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">De Guiringaud</persName> said that <persName
                        corresp="#p_SA_3">Aga Shahi</persName> had asked, during the period before
                    the Pakistani elections, that the French government not do anything to give the
                    impression that the contract was not going forward without change. <persName
                        corresp="#p_GLd_1">De Guiringaud</persName> had agreed to this request. He
                    agreed that if it became known that pressure was being applied on Pakistan this
                    would become an election issue which <persName corresp="#p_BZA_1"
                        >Bhutto</persName> might well make use of. (<persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">De
                        Guiringaud</persName> also said that <persName corresp="#p_SA_3">Aga
                        Shahi</persName> had conveyed a clear impression that he felt that some of
                    the charges against <persName corresp="#p_BZA_1">Bhutto</persName>, including
                    one of murder, were not without substance.)</p>
                <pb facs="0678" n="633" xml:id="pg_633"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">De Guiringaud</persName> asked that the contents of
                    this conversation with <persName corresp="#p_SA_3">Aga Shahi</persName> be kept
                    absolutely confidential. The Secretary promised to do so.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GLd_1">De Guiringaud</persName> recalled that Ambassador
                        <persName corresp="#p_HAA_1">Hartman</persName> had asked whether there had
                    been any transfers from France of equipment for the Pakistani reprocessing plant
                    after August 4.<note n="4" xml:id="d261fn4">See <ref target="#d259fn3">footnote
                            3, Document 259</ref>.</note> He said that the French government had
                    last authorized transfers of such equipment on July 16. Such authorizations were
                    valid for six months, and there was no way of determining within that period
                    when items authorized were shipped.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to Pakistan.]</p>
            </div>
